<br>
The Lifespike effect of the Thin Boned Rod sucks a little HP out of the target and gives it to you.  The Find Corpse effect of the Chipped Bone Rod spins you around to face in the direction of the nearest corpse of your target PC.  Each time you do it, it will use one charge; when there aren't any charges left, even if it doesn't disappear outright (some things do), you won't be able to trigger the effect anymore.  The most common example of a charged item is the SoW potion, called Blood of the Wolf, which casts a self-only version of Spirit of the Wolf; they are made by high-level shaman with the alchemy skill.  In fact, I have one with several charges in my packs right now, along with two Cloudy Potions (one charge of Invisibility, from NPC merchants) and a Vial of Vampire Blood (one charge of some +MR spell, from a glyphed ghoul in Mistmoore).<br>
<br>
Some items never run out of charges (they don't even have a number of charges listed).  The most famous example of an item with unlimited triggered charges is the Journeyman's Boots, which also casts SoW (probably a self-only version); it works just fine from a general inventory slot.  A slightly controversial one is the Pegasus Cloak, which casts levitate (probably a self-only version); it is needed for the magician epic quest, yet comes from a mid-30's *very* rare spawn in SK, where there are many groups just hanging out who are powerful enough to kill it.<br>
<br>
There are also items with unlimited random charges; as far as I know, they are all weapons.  When people speak of &quot;procs&quot;, they mean a weapon randomly &quot;processing&quot; its effect when you swing it (some weapons proc very often, others don't).  Procs are limited by level; as far as I know, triggered effects are not.  On a personal note, I am really looking forward to level 40, when I will stop getting the &quot;Your will is insufficient to command this weapon&quot; message from my Kunzar Ku'juch (a nice little 1hs from Kunark), and instead, it will start casting one of the necromancer Darkness spells (a damage-over-time and movement-debuff spell).  Triggered and random effects can be resisted by their targets, just as with any spell (if it's the kind of spell that you can't cast on a PC on a non-PvP server).<br>
<br>
Some very special items are neither triggered nor random.  They grant their effect to the wielder continuously, as long as they are wielded or worn.  I am the lucky owner of a Fishbone Earring, which gives me Enduring Breath; I simply don't need any air while I wear it.  It is one of my most valuable possessions, and I am very proud of getting it all by myself. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->      There are others, such as the Glowing Stone Band I've had my eyes on for awhile (so to speak); it grants Infravision when worn, and would be really handy when traveling by myself through outdoor zones at night.  As an aside, although all random procs are on weapons, not all effects on weapons are random; some are triggered (such as the Resurrection type effect of the cleric epic weapon), and some are constant (I've heard of weapons with constant Enduring Breath or Infravision, but I don't have to sacrifice damage output when using jewelry that way).<br>
<br>
Finally, there is a very special (and very new) class of item with an effect: food.  Some baked goods now have a minor effect when you eat them.  You can either put them in the most upper-left slot in the most upper-left bag in your inventory to make sure that they get eaten next. Right-clicking the food item causes you to eat it, but does not give you the benefits of the item. <br>
<br>
Welcome to the wonderful world of spells on items! <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->    <br>
<br>
Tudan<br>
Torvo<br>
<br>
